{
  "doc_id": "61405",
  "text": "The reactivity of NO and its higher oxides and nitrosothiol products (84) makes it likely that a variety of molecular targets are involved in its antiviral action. It has been shown that NO can inhibit ribonucleotide reductase [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , a rate-limiting enzyme in DNA synthesis, and NO can lead to the deamination of mammalian and bacterial DNA [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , which may be important antiviral mechanisms. Indeed, HSV-1 encodes its own ribonucleotide reductase and although it is not required for HSV-1 replication in vitro, it is necessary under conditions where the intracellular pool of deoxynucleotides is limited [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Thus, by inactivating this cellular and/or viral enzyme, NO may halt virus replication by directly inhibiting viral DNA synthesis.",
